Advantages of using a pulldown list

This pulldown list presents three models, which are stored in three different files: Model A.mml, Model B.mml and Model C.mml. When you select a file name from the pulldown list, the corresponding model will be loaded into the model container. The advantages of using a pulldown list are obvious: (1) The user does not need to scroll to view another container (compared with putting another model somewhere down the page). (2) The user does not need to open another page to see a different model (compared with putting another model on another page).

Disadvantages of using a pulldown list

The disadvantage of using the pulldown list is that it requires a bit more work on the designer&apos;s side. First, the designer has to make sure that the models to be loaded into the container from a pulldown list are explained in the current page&apos;s context. Make sure the models are not disconnected from the current context that is not going to change with respect to changing the content of a model container. There are extra steps and cautions involved in designing such a pulldown list, which we will discuss below.

Setting up a pulldown list

First, if you are using the Molecular Dynamics Containers, you have to save your models separately from the page, using the &quot;Save As&quot; menu item under the File menu of the model containers. The model files are different from the page files --- the extensions of the file names tell the difference: the model files have a suffix &quot;mml&quot; (or &quot;gbl&quot; if you are using the Mesoscale Simulation container), whereas the page files have a suffix &quot;cml&quot;. For example, in the above example, we have created three separate &quot;mml&quot; files: Model A.mml, Model B.mml, and Model C.mml. (Space characters in file names are ok, although you should generally avoid using strange characters in naming files.)

The saved &quot;mml&quot; or &quot;gbl&quot; files have to be in the same directory as where the &quot;cml&quot; page is stored. For example, the above three &quot;mml&quot; files are in the same directory where this page (&quot;loadmodels.cml&quot;) is located.

If you are using the Molecular Viewer Container, you have to copy the files containing the structure data (e.g. PDB files) to the directory where the &quot;cml&quot; page is located.

The default model that shows up when the page is loaded does not necessarily need to be put into the pulldown list. There is generally no such need, because reloading the whole page will reset the model container&apos;s content to the default model.

After you have finished saving your models, you can use the &quot;Insert&gt;Standard Controller for Model&gt;Combo Box&quot; menu to insert a pulldown list (i.e. combo box). When selecting that menu, you will first see a dialog window as follows:

 
This is a screenshot.

In this dialog window, select the model container from the &quot;Select a model to apply&quot; list, select the &quot;Import a model&quot; action from the &quot;Select an action&quot; list, and then type, in the order you would like the models to appear in the pulldown list, their file names in the &quot;Model list&quot; text field, separating them by a comma. You must not include the directory of the files.

After finishing these steps, a pulldown list will be inserted into the page and function in the way we describe above, provided the file names that have been entered are correct.

Cautions

(a) If you load a model from a pulldown list and then save the whole page, the default model will be overwritten. This is because when a page gets saved, the model container always saves whatever it contains at that moment.

(b) Saving a page that contains a pulldown list of models does not automatically save the models in the pulldown list as well. If you would like to save the models in the pulldown menu, you will have to open each of them and save them individually using the &quot;Save Frame As&quot; menu item under the File Menu of the model container.

(c) When you upload a page that contains a pulldown list of models, please use the &quot;Upload Current Activity Folder&quot;, instead of &quot;Upload Current Page&quot;. In addition to this, please make sure that you move this page to a new directory before uploading, to avoid the long wait for the program to scan through the files contained in your current working directory in order to determine which files should be incorporated into the upload.

(d) Ignore (c), if you are uploading an activity folder and have already followed the &quot;Making a New Directory for a New Activity&quot; rule.

